(it's like this for a variety of animals, especially hyenas) it's how evolution works. those who are weak will struggle and most likely die, whereas the strong survive - "survival of the fattest". question: Hi Lisa! Stumbled upon your blog last year and you are someone I look up to-- woohoo, women in games! I'm a lead designer at a small studio and have designing games for mobile for 2 years now. What are your thoughts on transitioning from mobile game design to AAA game design in terms of the kind of
answer: Aw, thanks! ^_^ (Oh God I really need to update my wordpress theme if people are stumbling upon my blog! :O).Also your question got cut off so I don't know the terms you were going to define, but I'll just take a best guess. Also note that having never been a designer on mobile games I'm speaking from one end of the spectrum here, but I do have a case study for you. My friend, David Shaver, transitioned from working primarily on mobile and casual games to becoming a designer at Respawn on Titanfall, so it is quite possible to do! However, most of what he did to sharpen up his AAA design skills to a quality level was done in his spare time on side projects. You can check that out here:  asked Dave for some words of wisdom on making the transition. Here's a summary of what he told me:1. Work your butt off on the side to build high quality work for the portfolio that demonstrates AAA skillset2. "Jack of all trades" skillsets, in his opinion, were more valued in mobile whereas AAA seeks out specialists. This isn't true of all places (Insomniac has more general designers, for example), but it certainly helps to be able to demonstrate a specific skillset (level design, combat, systems design, etc).3. Networking is important, and the mobile and AAA spheres can be a little different, so go out of your way to network with AAA folks.I'd say the skills you need in AAA depends on the types of games you want to work on, and then just being able to show off those skills, be that combat or quest design or whatever. I think whatever you're looking to get into, it's going to require supplemental portfolio work.I hope that answers the question! If it didn't, please feel free to follow-up :)

question: Everybody eventually becomes jaded in video games, how come you're still so nice to people?
answer: Interesting question! And one I had to ponder for a bit. I will be coming up on my 5-years-in-the-industry anniversary in June, which is a big milestone for me, since that’s when a lot of people drop out. I think I can attribute my resistance-to-jade to several things:1) I wasn’t one of those people who always knew they wanted to make games. I enjoyed playing them all my life, but making them didn’t really cross my mind as something I wanted to do. So I spent a lot of time agonizing over the fact that I had no idea what I wanted to do with my life. I tried many different things and wasn’t happy doing any of them. So when I finally dabbled in game design in graduate school and had a grand epiphany that I was in LOVE with the problem set that game development provided, it was very inspiring. It was a huge relief. In a way, every day I feel lucky that I managed to stumble into what I want to do with my life, and so that gratitude keeps me inspired through the challenges and low points of game development2) I work at an amazing studio. Seriously, Insomniac wins those “best small company to work for” awards so often that you can hardly walk around the place without tripping over one. It’s a studio that really values its employees and has a fantastic team environment, but the best thing about it is that as a company it’s constantly trying to get better. All the time it is trying things and figuring out ways to get even better, so even if there’s a rough time at work I feel confident that as a company we’ll figure out how to get better in the future. Being able to go to work and feel like I’m valued as a person and not having to live in fear really goes a long way to keeping the burn-out away.3) Helping people learn about games is refreshing. Especially in areas where there isn’t much of a scene, like my hometown in Kentucky, I like to try and connect with people and make them aware of the possibilities. Doing this in turn is really rewarding, and keeps me energized and motivated. It can be easy to take for granted how much you know and how much experience you have, so when I am able to provide an aspiring developer with an insight, it is very inspiring to me in return, and keeps me from getting jaded.4) I actively seek out ways to keep perspective on my life. I have a good friend who is a NICU doctor, and listening to her call stories is really sobering. If I ever feel stressed or despair about a game I’m working on, I try to remember her stories and realize that no matter what goes wrong for me, I’m not going to kill anyone with my mistakes. Watching Cosmos also helps, it makes me feel connected with everything and renders all my problems insignificant.5) Bein nice to people makes me happy! :D
